      "trust_model": {
        "actors": [
          {
            "id": "actor-evm-caller",
            "name": "EVM / State Module Caller",
            "description": "The Ethereum Virtual Machine and state management layer (state.py) that invokes trie operations such as trie_set, trie_get, root(), and state_root(). This is the primary consumer of the Merkle Patricia Trie. It drives account lookups, storage reads/writes, and state root computation during block processing."
          },
          {
            "id": "actor-transaction-originator",
            "name": "Transaction Originator",
            "description": "An external user or contract that submits transactions which ultimately cause state changes in the trie (account balance updates, storage slot writes, contract creation). Their data flows through the EVM into trie_set and eventually into _prepare_trie and root computation."
          },
          {
            "id": "actor-storage-root-callback",
            "name": "Storage Root Callback (get_storage_root)",
            "description": "A callback function (typically state.storage_root) that is passed into _prepare_trie and root(). It computes the storage root for Account objects. This actor represents the external computation that the trie trusts to return a correct 32-byte Root value for each address."
          },
          {
            "id": "actor-previous-trie",
            "name": "Previous Fork Trie (previous_trie)",
            "description": "The trie implementation from the preceding fork (Prague). The encode_node function delegates to previous_trie.encode_node for unrecognized node types, establishing a cross-fork trust dependency. This actor represents the backwards-compatibility layer."
          },
          {
            "id": "actor-rlp-encoder",
            "name": "RLP Encoder (ethereum_rlp)",
            "description": "The RLP serialization library used to encode trie nodes, accounts, transactions, receipts, and other objects. The trie trusts that rlp.encode produces deterministic, canonical output for any given input."
          },
          {
            "id": "actor-keccak256",
            "name": "Keccak-256 Hash Function",
            "description": "The cryptographic hash function used to hash trie keys (in secured mode), hash encoded nodes exceeding 32 bytes, and produce the state/storage root. The trie trusts this function for collision resistance and preimage resistance."
          },
          {
            "id": "actor-consensus-verifier",
            "name": "Consensus Verifier",
            "description": "External validators and light clients that verify the state root included in block headers. They depend on the trie producing a deterministic, canonical root from the same set of key-value pairs. Any non-determinism or divergence in root computation would cause consensus splits."
          }
        ],
        "trust_boundaries": [
          {
            "id": "tb-001",
            "from_actor": "actor-transaction-originator",
            "to_actor": "actor-evm-caller",
            "description": "Transaction data (addresses, storage keys, values, bytecode) crosses from an untrusted external originator into the EVM, which then writes it into the trie via trie_set. The trie itself does not validate semantic correctness of keys or values."
          },
          {
            "id": "tb-002",
            "from_actor": "actor-evm-caller",
            "to_actor": "actor-storage-root-callback",
            "description": "During _prepare_trie and root(), the trie calls get_storage_root(Address(preimage)) for every Account node. The returned Root is embedded directly into the encoded account without further validation. This is a critical trust boundary: if the callback returns an incorrect root, the entire state root is corrupted."
          },
          {
            "id": "tb-003",
            "from_actor": "actor-evm-caller",
            "to_actor": "actor-previous-trie",
            "description": "encode_node delegates to previous_trie.encode_node for node types not recognized by the current fork. The trie trusts that the previous fork's encoding is semantically compatible and produces canonical output. A bug or inconsistency in the previous fork's encoder would propagate into the current fork."
          },
          {
            "id": "tb-004",
            "from_actor": "actor-evm-caller",
            "to_actor": "actor-rlp-encoder",
            "description": "Multiple functions (encode_internal_node, encode_node, root) rely on rlp.encode for deterministic serialization. The 32-byte threshold check in encode_internal_node depends on the exact byte length of the RLP output. Non-canonical or non-deterministic RLP encoding would silently produce different state roots across implementations."
          },
          {
            "id": "tb-005",
            "from_actor": "actor-evm-caller",
            "to_actor": "actor-keccak256",
            "description": "keccak256 is used in three critical paths: (1) hashing keys in secured tries (_prepare_trie), (2) hashing encoded nodes >= 32 bytes (encode_internal_node), and (3) hashing short root nodes (root()). Any inconsistency in the hash function would break consensus."
          },
          {
            "id": "tb-006",
            "from_actor": "actor-evm-caller",
            "to_actor": "actor-consensus-verifier",
            "description": "The computed state root is published in block headers and verified by all nodes. This is the ultimate trust boundary: all internal trie operations must produce a bit-identical root for the same logical state. The boundary is from the trie computation outward to the consensus layer."
          },
          {
            "id": "tb-007",
            "from_actor": "actor-transaction-originator",
            "to_actor": "actor-keccak256",
            "description": "In secured tries, user-supplied keys (addresses) are hashed with keccak256 before insertion. This provides a trust boundary that prevents adversarial key ordering attacks. Without this hashing, an attacker could craft keys to create deeply unbalanced tries, causing DoS."
          },
          {
            "id": "tb-008",
            "from_actor": "actor-evm-caller",
            "to_actor": "actor-evm-caller",
            "description": "Internal boundary within the trie between the flat key-value store (trie_set/trie_get operating on _data dict) and the Merkle tree construction (patricialize/encode_internal_node). The _prepare_trie function bridges these two representations. Any corruption of _data or incorrect encoding in this transformation breaks the trie."
          }
        ],
        "assumptions": [
          {
            "id": "asm-001",
            "text": "The RLP encoder (ethereum_rlp) produces canonical, deterministic output for any given input. All implementations must agree on the exact byte representation. This is critical because the 32-byte threshold in encode_internal_node depends on exact encoded length."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-002",
            "text": "keccak256 is collision-resistant and produces consistent output across all implementations. Two different internal node encodings must never produce the same hash. Pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a node that hashes to a target value."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-003",
            "text": "The get_storage_root callback, when provided, returns the correct, finalized 32-byte storage root for the given address. The trie asserts (storage_root is not None) but does not validate the root's correctness. A corrupted storage root would propagate into the state root silently."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-004",
            "text": "The previous fork's trie implementation (Prague trie) encodes unrecognized types correctly and compatibly. The fallback in encode_node trusts previous_trie.encode_node without validating the output, assuming backwards compatibility is maintained across fork boundaries."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-005",
            "text": "All nibble values in byte-to-nibble conversions are in range [0, 15]. The nibble_list_to_compact and bytes_to_nibble_list functions assume well-formed input. Malformed nibble lists could produce incorrect compact encodings, corrupting trie paths."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-006",
            "text": "The Trie._data dictionary is only modified through trie_set (which enforces the default-value deletion invariant). Direct manipulation of _data would violate INV-006/INV-007 and could leave ghost entries that corrupt the Merkle root."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-007",
            "text": "copy_trie performs a shallow copy of _data. This is safe only because trie values are frozen (immutable) objects. If mutable objects were stored in the trie, modifications after copy would affect both the original and the copy, corrupting snapshots and rollbacks."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-008",
            "text": "The patricialize function's recursion terminates because the level parameter strictly increases with each recursive call (INV-028). If keys could be constructed such that level does not advance, infinite recursion (stack overflow) would result."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-009",
            "text": "Account, Receipt, and Uint types must never appear as the value in a BranchNode's value position (INV-027). The patricialize function raises AssertionError if this occurs. This assumes the EVM and state module never produce a state where an Account's encoded key has the same length as the trie level."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-010",
            "text": "The empty trie root is always keccak256(RLP(b'')), which equals the constant EMPTY_TRIE_ROOT. All implementations must agree on this value for empty state/storage tries."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-011",
            "text": "Encoded values produced by encode_node are never empty bytes (b''). _prepare_trie asserts this invariant (INV-017). An empty encoded value would represent a logical inconsistency: a key is present in _data but its value encodes to nothing."
          },
          {
            "id": "asm-012",
            "text": "The iteration order of trie._data.items() in _prepare_trie does not affect the final root because patricialize constructs a canonical tree structure based on key prefixes, not insertion order. The Merkle Patricia Trie is order-independent by design."
          }
        ],
        "stride_analysis": [
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-001",
            "threat_type": "Denial of Service",
            "description": "A transaction originator can craft storage keys designed to create pathological trie structures. Without key hashing (unsecured tries), an attacker could create deeply nested paths with long common prefixes, causing the patricialize function to recurse excessively or branch nodes to be heavily unbalanced. Even with secured tries, large volumes of state writes increase trie computation cost.",
            "mitigation": "Secured tries (trie.secured=True) hash all keys with keccak256 before insertion, randomizing the key distribution and preventing deliberate key-ordering attacks. Gas costs for SSTORE operations limit the volume of state writes per transaction."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-001",
            "threat_type": "Tampering",
            "description": "Malicious input data (crafted account values, storage values) could potentially cause unexpected behavior in encode_node if the type dispatch logic does not handle all edge cases. The fallback to previous_trie.encode_node for unrecognized types could be exploited if a new type is introduced that the current fork does not handle but the previous fork encodes differently.",
            "mitigation": "The type dispatch in encode_node uses isinstance checks with explicit type lists. The assertion in _prepare_trie that encoded values are non-empty provides a safety net. The assertion in patricialize that Account/Receipt/Uint types cannot appear in BranchNode value positions adds type-level protection."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-002",
            "threat_type": "Tampering",
            "description": "If the get_storage_root callback returns an incorrect storage root for an address, the encoded account will contain a wrong storage root hash, which will propagate through the trie all the way to the state root. The trie only asserts that storage_root is not None but does not validate its length, format, or correctness.",
            "mitigation": "The callback is provided by the trusted state module (state.storage_root), which computes the root from the actual storage trie. The assertion (storage_root is not None) catches null references. The Root type alias (Hash32) provides type-level constraints on length."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-002",
            "threat_type": "Spoofing",
            "description": "If an attacker could substitute the get_storage_root callback with a malicious implementation, they could inject arbitrary storage roots into account encodings, effectively spoofing the storage state of any account. This would allow an attacker to claim arbitrary storage contents.",
            "mitigation": "The callback is constructed within the trusted state module and passed directly. There is no external API for supplying an arbitrary callback. The function signature is enforced by Python's type system."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-003",
            "threat_type": "Tampering",
            "description": "The previous fork's encode_node could produce different encodings than expected if it is modified or contains bugs. Since encode_node falls through to previous_trie.encode_node for unrecognized types without validating the result, any inconsistency would silently propagate into the current fork's state root.",
            "mitigation": "The fallback mechanism is by design: it provides backwards compatibility for types inherited from previous forks. The reference spec is authoritative, and all client implementations must match its behavior. Cross-fork testing validates encoding consistency."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-003",
            "threat_type": "Elevation of Privilege",
            "description": "If a new node type is introduced that neither the current fork nor the previous fork handles correctly, it would silently fall through the type dispatch chain across multiple forks. This could result in an unrecognized type being encoded by a very old fork's logic that was not designed to handle it, potentially bypassing validation constraints added in newer forks.",
            "mitigation": "Each fork explicitly lists the types it handles. The isinstance chain in encode_node provides a deterministic dispatch order. The assertion in _prepare_trie that encoded values are non-empty catches cases where a type produces no encoding."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-004",
            "threat_type": "Tampering",
            "description": "If the RLP encoder produces non-canonical encodings (e.g., different byte ordering, different length prefixes for the same data), the 32-byte threshold check in encode_internal_node would behave differently across implementations. Nodes that should be hashed might be left unencoded, or vice versa. This would cause state root divergence and consensus failure.",
            "mitigation": "The Ethereum RLP specification defines a strict canonical encoding. The ethereum_rlp library is the reference implementation. All client implementations must produce bit-identical RLP output for the same input to maintain consensus."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-004",
            "threat_type": "Information Disclosure",
            "description": "The decision to return unencoded data (when RLP < 32 bytes) versus a keccak256 hash (when >= 32 bytes) creates a size-dependent information boundary. For small nodes, the full node content is exposed in the parent node. An observer of the trie structure can determine node sizes and partially reconstruct trie contents from internal node references.",
            "mitigation": "This is by design in the Merkle Patricia Trie specification. The 32-byte threshold is a space optimization, not a privacy mechanism. Ethereum state is public by design. Secured tries hash keys but not values."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-005",
            "threat_type": "Tampering",
            "description": "If the keccak256 implementation produces inconsistent hashes (e.g., due to a bug, platform-specific behavior, or a supply-chain attack on the crypto library), all secured trie key lookups would fail, all node hashing would produce wrong results, and the state root would be incorrect. This is the most critical cryptographic dependency.",
            "mitigation": "The keccak256 implementation is from the ethereum.crypto.hash module, which wraps a well-tested cryptographic library. The hash is standardized (FIPS 202 / SHA-3). All client implementations must use the same algorithm."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-005",
            "threat_type": "Spoofing",
            "description": "In secured tries, keys are hashed with keccak256 to prevent an attacker from choosing their position in the trie. If keccak256 were broken (collision attacks), an attacker could craft two different addresses that hash to the same trie key, causing one account's state to overwrite another's.",
            "mitigation": "Keccak-256 provides 128-bit collision resistance. No practical collision attacks are known. The Ethereum ecosystem continuously monitors the security of its cryptographic primitives."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-006",
            "threat_type": "Repudiation",
            "description": "If the trie root computation is non-deterministic (e.g., due to dict ordering issues in _prepare_trie), different nodes could compute different state roots for the same state. A block producer could claim one root while validators compute another, leading to disputes about the correct state. The block producer could repudiate the state transition.",
            "mitigation": "The patricialize function constructs a canonical tree structure based on key prefixes, not insertion order. The Merkle Patricia Trie is deterministic by design: the same set of key-value pairs always produces the same root. Python dict ordering (insertion order since 3.7) does not affect the root because the tree structure depends only on key content."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-006",
            "threat_type": "Denial of Service",
            "description": "Computing the state root requires traversing the entire trie (_prepare_trie iterates all entries, patricialize recurses over all keys). An attacker who can create many state entries (accounts, storage slots) can increase the computational cost of root computation, potentially causing block processing timeouts.",
            "mitigation": "Gas costs for state-modifying operations (SSTORE, CREATE, CALL with value) limit the number of state changes per block. State rent and EIP-4444 (history expiry) are longer-term mitigations. The patricialize algorithm is O(n * k) where n is the number of keys and k is the key length, which is bounded."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-007",
            "threat_type": "Denial of Service",
            "description": "Without key hashing in secured tries, an attacker could choose keys (addresses) with long common prefixes, forcing the patricialize function to create deeply nested extension nodes. This would increase the depth of the trie and the cost of proof generation and verification. With key hashing, the cost is bounded by the hash output length (32 bytes = 64 nibbles).",
            "mitigation": "All state and storage tries use secured=True, meaning keys are hashed with keccak256 before insertion. This ensures keys are uniformly distributed across the 256-bit key space, bounding trie depth to 64 nibbles. The common_prefix_length function is O(min(len(a), len(b))) which is bounded by the hash length."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-008",
            "threat_type": "Tampering",
            "description": "The internal boundary between the flat _data dict and the Merkle tree relies on _prepare_trie correctly transforming all entries. If _data contains entries with value == trie.default (which should have been deleted by trie_set), these ghost entries would be encoded and included in the Merkle tree, producing an incorrect root. The assertion (encoded_value != b'') partially catches this but not all cases.",
            "mitigation": "trie_set enforces the invariant that default values are never stored in _data (INV-006, INV-007). The assertion in _prepare_trie that encoded values are non-empty provides defense-in-depth. The copy_trie function preserves this invariant through shallow copying."
          },
          {
            "trust_boundary_id": "tb-008",
            "threat_type": "Elevation of Privilege",
            "description": "Direct manipulation of trie._data (bypassing trie_set) could insert values that violate the trie's invariants. For example, inserting a value equal to trie.default would create a phantom entry visible in the Merkle root but not semantically meaningful. The Python dataclass does not enforce access control on _data.",
            "mitigation": "The underscore prefix on _data is a Python convention indicating it should not be accessed directly. The state module consistently uses trie_set and trie_get. However, there is no runtime enforcement preventing direct access. Code review and testing are the primary safeguards."
          }
        ]
      },
      "_source_file": "outputs/01d_PARTIAL_W0B1_1770284080.json"
    }
  ],
